 &lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="knowledge-sharing"&gt;Knowledge Sharing&lt;a href="#knowledge-sharing" class="heading-anchor" aria-label="Link to this section"&gt;&lt;svg class="h-4 w-4" aria-hidden="true" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24"&gt;&lt;g fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"&gt;&lt;path d="M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"/&gt;&lt;path d="M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"/&gt;&lt;/g&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Emphasizes knowledge sharing to avoid information silos. Every isolated silo gives rise to a problem, so building a knowledge base within the team is an important first step.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;In team learning, building a psychologically safe environment for less experienced team members is important.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h3 id="team-interaction-patterns"&gt;Team Interaction Patterns&lt;a href="#team-interaction-patterns" class="heading-anchor" aria-label="Link to this section"&gt;&lt;svg class="h-4 w-4" aria-hidden="true" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24"&gt;&lt;g fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"&gt;&lt;path d="M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"/&gt;&lt;path d="M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"/&gt;&lt;/g&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;table&gt;
 &lt;thead&gt;
 &lt;tr&gt;
 &lt;th&gt;Recommended Patterns&lt;/th&gt;
 &lt;th&gt;Anti-Patterns&lt;/th&gt;
 &lt;/tr&gt;
 &lt;/thead&gt;
 &lt;tbody&gt;
 &lt;tr&gt;
 &lt;td&gt;Basic questions or mistakes are guided in the right direction&lt;/td&gt;
 &lt;td&gt;Basic questions are called out, and the person asking is punished&lt;/td&gt;
 &lt;/tr&gt;
 &lt;tr&gt;
 &lt;td&gt;Explanations are given to help the questioner learn&lt;/td&gt;
 &lt;td&gt;Explanations are given to show off&lt;/td&gt;
 &lt;/tr&gt;
 &lt;tr&gt;
 &lt;td&gt;Responses are friendly, patient, and helpful&lt;/td&gt;
 &lt;td&gt;Responses are arrogant, sarcastic, and unconstructive&lt;/td&gt;
 &lt;/tr&gt;
 &lt;tr&gt;
 &lt;td&gt;Interactions are collaborative discussions aimed at finding solutions&lt;/td&gt;
 &lt;td&gt;Interactions are arguments designed to produce &amp;ldquo;winners&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;losers&amp;rdquo;&lt;/td&gt;
 &lt;/tr&gt;
 &lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;h3 id="closing-thoughts"&gt;Closing Thoughts&lt;a href="#closing-thoughts" class="heading-anchor" aria-label="Link to this section"&gt;&lt;svg class="h-4 w-4" aria-hidden="true" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24"&gt;&lt;g fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"&gt;&lt;path d="M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"/&gt;&lt;path d="M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"/&gt;&lt;/g&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Start small: ask questions and write things down.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;At the system level, encourage and reward those who take time to teach and expand their expertise for the benefit of others, their team, and the organization - not just for themselves.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h2 id="how-to-lead-a-team"&gt;How to Lead a Team?&lt;a href="#how-to-lead-a-team" class="heading-anchor" aria-label="Link to this section"&gt;&lt;svg class="h-4 w-4" aria-hidden="true" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24"&gt;&lt;g fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"&gt;&lt;path d="M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"/&gt;&lt;path d="M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"/&gt;&lt;/g&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
 &lt;blockquote
 class="border-primary bg-muted/30 hover:bg-muted/40 my-6 rounded-r-lg border-l-4 py-4 pr-4 pl-6 italic transition-all duration-200 ease-out hover:translate-x-1"
 &gt;
 &lt;div class="prose prose-sm max-w-none"&gt;
 &lt;p&gt;Traditional managers worry about how to complete tasks, while great managers worry about what tasks will be completed (and trust their team to figure out how to solve them).&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>gcp</title><link>https://ezrawu-tw.github.io/en/posts/gcp/</link><pubDate>Tue, 28 Oct 2025 12:07:45 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://ezrawu-tw.github.io/en/posts/gcp/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;slug: gcp&lt;/p&gt;
